RED FLAG 3 — Peter Greven Magnesium Stearate: wrong column extracted
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Bug: Peter Greven Ligamed Mag Stearate CoA has TWO numeric columns:
   - "Content measured or range" (actual measured values in ppb)
   - "Report Limit (RL)" (analytical detection limit in ppb)

For elements marked "<RL" (below detection): the Report Limit column is 
NOT the measured value.
For elements marked with a numeric content (e.g., V ~2030 ppb): the 
measured value is in the "Content" column, and RL is the detection limit.

Extractor is reading Report Limit column for ALL elements, giving:
   V = 0.239 µg/g  (should be 2.03 µg/g measured)
   Ni = 0.098 µg/g (should be 1.34 µg/g measured)
   Pb = 0.285 µg/g (correct interpretation: <0.285, so use RL as worst case)

Regulatory impact for Diazoxide Choline: minimal (Mag Stearate is 0.3% of 
product mass), but for products where Mag Stearate is a higher fraction, 
this understates exposure by 10x.

Fix in annexure_converter.py Peter Greven CoA extractor:

1. Recognize the Peter Greven CoA table structure with columns:
   Element | Class | Potentially present | Intentionally added | 
   Analytical method | Content measured or range | Report Limit (RL) | 
   Monitoring
   
2. Extraction rules per element row:
   IF "Content measured or range" contains a numeric value (e.g., "~2030"):
       extracted_value_ppm = numeric_value / 1000  (ppb to ppm)
       extraction_type = "measured"
   ELIF "Content" contains "<RL":
       extracted_value_ppm = report_limit_ppb / 1000  (worst case)
       extraction_type = "below_LOD"
   ELSE:
       flag for manual review
   
3. Include unit conversion metadata. Peter Greven reports in ppb.
   Always convert ppb → ppm before emitting.

Acceptance for Peter Greven Ligamed Mag Stearate:
   V:  2.030 µg/g  (from measured ~2030 ppb)
   Ni: 1.340 µg/g  (from measured ~1340 ppb)
   Ba: 1.790 µg/g  (from measured ~1790 ppb)
   Li: 0.060 µg/g  (from measured ~60 ppb)
   Cu: 0.160 µg/g  (from measured ~160 ppb)
   Cr: 0.310 µg/g  (from measured ~310 ppb)
   All others: <RL/1000 in ppm (below detection worst case)

Approved TSR values for these elements should match to 3 decimals.

