RED FLAG 4 — Roquette Dextrose "<30% of Perm. Conc." misextraction
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Bug: Roquette Dextrose Anhydrous C CoA reports results as percentages of 
ICH Q3D permitted concentration:
   "Results: <30% of Perm. Conc." per element
   
Extractor treats "<30%" as a numeric value and defaults to placeholder 
50 µg/g for all 7 elements. This is the single most impactful bug in the 
Esomeprazole run — Dextrose is 88% of drug product mass, so wrong values 
here dominate every column total.

Actual approved TSR values (interpreted correctly as 30% of Option 1 
concentration):
   Pb: 0.15 µg/g  (30% of 0.5 = 0.15)
   As: 0.45 µg/g  (30% of 1.5 = 0.45)
   Cd: 0.15 µg/g  (30% of 0.5 = 0.15)
   Hg: 0.9 µg/g   (30% of 3.0 = 0.9)
   Co: 1.5 µg/g   (30% of 5.0 = 1.5)
   V:  3.0 µg/g   (30% of 10.0 = 3.0)
   Ni: 6.0 µg/g   (30% of 20.0 = 6.0)

Fix in annexure_converter.py:

1. Detect the "<X% of Perm. Conc." pattern (case-insensitive, handles 
   variants: "% of Permitted Concentration", "% Perm Conc", "of ICH Q3D 
   Perm. Conc.").

2. Compute value as: (X/100) × Option_1_oral_concentration[element]
   Where Option 1 oral concentration comes from ICH Q3D R2 Table A.2.2.

3. Fallback: If X% cannot be parsed but "<30%" or "meets Option 1" appears, 
   use 30% of Option 1 as worst-case interpretation. Do NOT default to 
   50 µg/g placeholder.

Reference constants (ICH Q3D R2 Option 1 oral, µg/g):
   Class 1: Pb=0.5, As=1.5, Cd=0.5, Hg=3.0
   Class 2A: Co=5.0, V=10.0, Ni=20.0
   Class 2B: Pd=10.0, Se=15.0, Tl=0.8, Au=30.0, Ir=10.0, Os=10.0, 
             Rh=10.0, Ru=10.0, Ag=15.0, Pt=10.0
   Class 3: Li=55.0, Sb=120.0, Ba=140.0, Mo=300.0, Cu=300.0, Sn=600.0, 
             Cr=1100.0

Acceptance:
Roquette Dextrose extracts Pb=0.15, As=0.45, Cd=0.15, Hg=0.9, Co=1.5, 
V=3.0, Ni=6.0 (Esomeprazole run matches approved).

