RED FLAG 6 — LOD/LOQ vs measured value interpretation
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Bug: Vendor CoAs use different notations for "not detected":
   "Not detected"
   "Below LOD"  
   "Below LOQ"
   "<0.05"
   "<LOD"
   "ND"
   Numeric value with < prefix

Extractor treats all of these differently:
   Sometimes uses the LOD/LOQ value (worst case, conservative — correct)
   Sometimes uses 0.05 as a placeholder (wrong)
   Sometimes uses 50 (default placeholder — wrong)

Fix in annexure_converter.py:

1. Recognize "not detected" family notations:
   patterns = ["not detected", "nd", "n.d.", "below lod", "below loq", 
               "<lod", "<loq"]

2. When these appear, look for the LOD/LOQ value in the same row or in 
   header rows above (Method Detection Limit, MDL, LOQ, Quantification 
   Limit).

3. Use the LOD/LOQ value as the worst-case measured value:
   effective_ppm = LOD_ppm (worst-case interpretation for exposure calc)
   evidence_type = "below_LOD" (audit trail)

4. Never default to 0.05 or 50 or any other placeholder. If LOD cannot be 
   extracted, flag for manual review and use 0.0 (with warning in log).

5. When vendor CoA says "3 batches all Not Detected" and LOQ=0.1 ppm, use 
   0.1 as the effective value (worst-case, conservative, defensible).

Reference: Approved TSRs use LOQ as worst-case value in nearly all "not 
detected" cases — this is the DRL scientific convention.

Acceptance:
BASF Kollidon CL (all <0.05 ppm): extracts as 0.05 for all elements 
(not zero, not 50).
Peter Greven "<RL" for most elements: extracts as RL value (not 50).
Vertellus Triethyl Citrate "<20 ppb": extracts as 0.020 µg/g (not 20).

